# Command zcurl

## What does this command do:

It's a curl alternative with stunning box-style output that makes API testing actually enjoyable.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: npm install -g @12britz/zcurl
For Raspberry Pi install using: npm install -g @12britz/zcurl
For Mac install using: npm install -g @12britz/zcurl

## Command path

For Fedora run: /home/kinscoe/.local/bin/zcurl
For Raspberry Pi run: /usr/local/bin/zcurl
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/zcurl

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/12britz/zcurl

## Command options

# Make a GET request
zcurl https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Make a POST request with JSON body
zcurl -X POST https://api.example.com/endpoint -d '{"key":"value"}'

# Set a request header
zcurl -H "Authorization: Bearer mytoken" https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Basic auth or Bearer token
zcurl --auth user:pass https://api.example.com/endpoint
zcurl --auth mytoken https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Add query parameters
zcurl -q key=value -q page=1 https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Force JSON content type and pretty output
zcurl -j -X POST https://api.example.com/endpoint -d '{"key":"val"}'

# Force form-urlencoded content type
zcurl -f -X POST https://api.example.com/endpoint -d 'key=value'

# Show full request and response details (verbose)
zcurl -v https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Follow redirects
zcurl -L https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Skip TLS verification
zcurl -k https://self-signed.example.com/endpoint

# Set timeout (milliseconds or seconds)
zcurl --timeout 5000 https://api.example.com/endpoint
zcurl --max-time 5 https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Save response body to file
zcurl -o response.json https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Download response as file
zcurl --download https://api.example.com/file.zip

# Send N concurrent requests (load testing)
zcurl -n 100 -c 10 https://api.example.com/endpoint

# Replay the last request
zcurl --replay

# Show request history
zcurl --history
